04284nam a22006255i 9780292794795DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212007txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927947957 a10.7560/7146182doi  a(DE-B1597)587249  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aBM755.C6bC64 2007eb 7aBIO0180002bisacsh04a296.8/341092aB2221 aCohen, Rabbi Henry, Rabbi Henry, II, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aKindler of Souls :bRabbi Henry Cohen of Texas /cRabbi Henry, II Cohen, Rabbi Henry. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2007  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrologue -- tChapter 1. From Torah to Tennyson -- tChapter 2. Being Jewish in Jamaica -- tChapter 3. Little Jerusalem -- tChapter 4. Planting Roots -- tChapter 5. The Storm and Its Impact -- tChapter 6. From Health to Horror -- tChapter 7. “Through the Gateway of Galveston” -- tChapter 8. “Dear Graduates”: On Being a Rabbi -- tChapter 9. From the Kaiser to the Klan -- tChapter 10. Prison Reform: The Rabbi and the Convict -- tChapter 11. Family Matters and Memory: 1930–1950 -- tChapter 12. The Rabbi and His Times -- tAppendix: Selected Poems by Rabbi Henry Cohen -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn September 1930, the New York Times published a list of the clergy whom Rabbi Stephen Wise considered "the ten foremost religious leaders in this country." The list included nine Christians and Rabbi Henry Cohen of Galveston, Texas. Little-known today, Henry Cohen was a rabbi to be reckoned with, a man Woodrow Wilson called "the foremost citizen of Texas" who also impressed the likes of William Howard Taft and Clarence Darrow. Cohen's fleeting fame, however, was built not on powerful friendships but on a lifetime of service to needy Jews—as well as gentiles—in London, South Africa, Jamaica, and, for the last sixty-four years of his life, Galveston, Texas. More than 10,000 Jews, mostly from Eastern Europe, arrived in Galveston in the early twentieth century. Rabbi Cohen greeted many of the new arrivals in Yiddish, then helped them find jobs through a network that extended throughout the Southwest and Midwest United States. The "Galveston Movement," along with Cohen's pioneering work reforming Texas prisons and fighting the Ku Klux Klan, made the rabbi a legend in his time. As this portrait shows, however, he was also a lovable mensch to his grandson. Rabbi Henry Cohen II reminisces about his grandfather's jokes while placing the legendary rabbi in historical context, creating the best picture yet of this important Texan, a man perhaps best summarized by Rabbi Wise in the New York Times as "a soul who touches and kindles souls."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aRabbiszTexaszGalvestonvBiography. 0aReform JudaismzTexaszGalveston. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Religious.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/71461840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292794795423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292794795/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK